        <h2 class="font-l">Fonts</h2>

        <p>
          Responsive, viewport based, fonts should be restricted to use on headings
          and isolated blocks of text. Avoid using it on copy paragraphs and long
          blocks of text. I would also advise against using medium or large sizes
          nearby normal (non-responsive) blocks of text because these viewport
          based texts can actually end up <em>smaller</em> at certain screen sizes.
        </p>

        <p>
          I've never been a fan of styling <code>h1, h2, h3</code>, etc directly or by tying their
          size and style to their heading number. What if h2 and h4 should visually
          look the same but not in every instance? Over time and with multiple
          maintainers the CSS and HTML end up tied in knots.
        </p>

        <p>
          The solution is simple; just define font styles to utility classes and apply
          where required regardless of the markup. If you want to style one list item
          to look like some hero text, go right ahead! It does not matter, the semantics
          are in your HTML markup and content.
        </p>
      </div>

